This is the API proposal and feature set for object (de)serialization.

Design points:
- Due to time constraints, and to gather feedback, the feature set is minimal for 3.0.
- Simple POCO object scenarios are targeted.
- API designed to be extensible for new features in subsequent releases and by the community.
- Use attributes for defining the various options, but still support modifications at run-time.
- High performance using IL Emit with fallback to standard reflection for compat.

# API
## JsonConverter
This static class is the main entry point. It uses extension methods on Utf8JsonReader\Writer, and will likely have future methods serving Utf8String and others. The name "converter" was chosen over "serializer" because of the likelihood of these future methods, and for similar reasons "ToJson\FromJson" was selected over "Read\Write" or "Serialize\Deserialize".

```cs
namespace System.Text.Json
{
    public static class JsonConverter
    {
        public static T FromJson<T>(this Utf8JsonReader reader, JsonConverterSettings settings = null);
        public static void ToJson(this Utf8JsonWriter writer, object value, JsonConverterSettings settings = null);

        // Example of future methods
        // public static T FromJson<T>(Utf8String value, JsonConverterSettings settings = null);
        // public static Utf8String ToJson(object value, JsonConverterSettings settings = null);
    }
```

## JsonConverterSettings
This class contains the settings that are used during (de)serialization. Almost all settings can be specified though design-time attributes so this class would only be used when the options are not known at design-time, or when settings may vary at run-time for a given POCO class.

All of the design-time attributes are automatically used and cannot be disabled or removed\changed. _However, pending feedback we could allow this._

If an instance of `JsonConverterSettings` is not specified when calling FromJson()\ToJson() then a default instance is used which is immutable and private. Having a global\static instance is not a viable feature because of unintended side affects when more than one area of code changes the global settings. Having a thread\context mechanism is possible, but will only be added pending feedback.

The AddAttribute allows for run-time options by using the same design-time Attributes. These run-time attributes are stored on the `JsonConverterSettings` instance and merged with the design-time attributes.

The `ClassMaterializer` property affects the internal implementation of how classes are created and properties\setters are invoked. The `Default` value will first attempt to use `ReflectionEmit` (IL Emit) which is fast but not supported on all platforms. If a `NotSupportedException` is raised, then the materializer will fall back to `Reflection` which uses standard reflection which is supported on (almost) all platforms. In the future, a code gen (or extended IL Emit) option may be added for performance.

```cs
namespace System.Text.Json
{
    public class JsonConverterSettings
    {
        public JsonConverterSettings() { }
        public JsonClassMaterializer ClassMaterializer { get; set; }
        public void AddAttribute(System.Reflection.ICustomAttributeProvider type, Attribute attribute);
        public IEnumerable<TAttribute> GetAttributes<TAttribute>(System.Reflection.ICustomAttributeProvider type, bool inherit = false) where TAttribute : Attribute;
    }

    public enum JsonClassMaterializers
    {
        Default = 0,
        Reflection = 1,
        ReflectionEmit = 2,
    }
}
```

## Using Attributes for settings
As previously mentioned, design-time attributes are used to specify the settings with an option to add them at run-time. This reduces the concept count as it prevents two sets of classes to specify both the Attribute and run-time classes. It also allows the run-time settings to override the design-time settings.

A given Attribute class can typically be applied to a Property, Class and Assembly with the lower-level (e.g. Property) having precedence of the higher-level (Assembly). This allows for global settings with override capability.

For Attribute classes with several properties\settings, a Null value for a given setting indicates no setting, and the lower-level setting should be used.

## JsonPropertyAttribute (common, simple settings for a property)
This attribute specifies the settings that pertain to a POCO property (and field pending feedback).

The settings here are simple values; more complex settings or extensible settings have their own attributes. This class prevents an explosion of perhaps 10-20 additional classes once more settings are added.

```cs
namespace System.Text.Json
{
    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Assembly | AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Field | AttributeTargets.Property, AllowMultiple = false)]
    public partial class JsonPropertyAttribute : System.Attribute
    {
        public JsonPropertyAttribute() { }
        public bool? IncludeNullValues { get; set; }

        // Several more options TBD
    }
```

## Property Name feature
These attributes determine how a property name can be different between Json and POCO. New attributes can easily be added by anyone by creating a new attribute derived from `JsonPropertyNamePolicyAttribute`.

```cs
namespace System.Text.Json
{
    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Assembly | AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Field | AttributeTargets.Property, AllowMultiple = false)]
    public class CamelCasingConverterAttribute : JsonPropertyNamePolicyAttribute
    {
        public CamelCasingConverterAttribute() { }
        public override ValueConverter<string, string> GetConverter();
    }

    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Field | AttributeTargets.Property, AllowMultiple = false)]
    public class JsonPropertyNameAttribute : JsonPropertyNamePolicyAttribute
    {
        public JsonPropertyNameAttribute() { }
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public override ValueConverter<string, string> GetConverter();
    }
}
```

## Policy namespace
The `System.Text.Json.Policies` namespace contains classes that are not normally used by the consumer. Instead, they are used by an author when deriving\extending existing attributes. Having them in a separate namespace reduces the class count of the main namespace.

```cs
namespace System.Text.Json.Policies
{
    public class CamelCasingPolicy : ValueConverter<string, string>
    {
        public CamelCasingPolicy();
        public override string FromJson(string jsonValue);
        public override string ToJson(string objectValue);
    }

    public class JsonPropertyAttribute : Attribute
    {
        public JsonPropertyAttribute();
        public bool? IncludeNullValues { get; set; }
    }

    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Assembly | AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Field | AttributeTargets.Property, AllowMultiple = false)]
    public abstract class JsonPropertyNamePolicyAttribute : Attribute
    {
        protected JsonPropertyNamePolicyAttribute();
        public abstract ValueConverter<string, string> GetConverter();
    }

    public class PropertyNamePolicy : ValueConverter<string, string>
    {
        public PropertyNamePolicy(string name);
        public string Name { get; }
        public override string FromJson(string jsonValue);
        public override string ToJson(string objectValue);
    }

    public abstract class ValueConverter<TJson, TObject>
    {
        protected ValueConverter() { }
        public abstract TObject FromJson(TJson jsonValue);
        public abstract TJson ToJson(TObject objectValue);
    }
```

